While Virgil's usage is well-documented, Poe's familiarity with the term likely stems from German author Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, a writer Poe greatly admired.  

This admiration is evident in Karl J. Arndt's observation that Poe's "Dream-Land" seems to echo Goethe's poem "The King of Thulé," which depicts a grieving king who ultimately chooses death after his wife's passing.  Both poems share thematic similarities, particularly in their portrayal of loss, melancholy, and a desolate landscape. 

Goethe's "Faust," a celebrated two-part poetic drama, also likely influenced Poe. "The King of Thulé" appears within the second part of "Faust," published in 1832, the year of Goethe's death.  Poe's use of "Thulé" in "Dream-Land" and "The Pit and the Pendulum" suggests he was deeply familiar with Goethe's work. The themes and imagery in "Dream-Land" resonate with those in "The King of Thulé," possibly reflecting Poe's own struggles with grief and his coping mechanisms. 

Poe's awareness of Goethe's writings wasn't solely due to his admiration for the English poet Alfred, Lord Tennyson, who himself was influenced by Goethe. Additionally, numerous reproductions and translations of Goethe's work would have exposed Poe to his writing during his lifetime.

Could a customer who slipped and fell on an applesauce spill in a California grocery store be awarded punitive damages if they could prove the store manager acted with malice? The manager was informed about the spill twice but didn't clean it for half an hour because he was eating dinner. 

A judge is unlikely to immediately dismiss a claim for punitive damages in this situation. To justify punitive damages, the plaintiff must demonstrate that the defendant's actions were intentional and reckless, disregarding the potential harm they could cause, and that the actions were morally reprehensible.  The customer could argue that the manager should have known the risk of not cleaning the spill because there had been several previous slip-and-fall accidents at the store. The customer could also argue that the manager's actions were despicable because he ignored multiple warnings about the spill despite a history of similar incidents. 

The case involves an employee informing the manager about an applesauce spill at 5:00 PM on October 13, 2009. The manager, Paul Martin, refused to address the issue, saying he was on a dinner break. Another employee brought it to his attention again at 5:15 PM, and he gave the same response. At 5:30 PM, a customer, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill, injuring her back.  Prior to this incident, there had been five reported slip-and-fall accidents at the store that year. Palmer is now suing the store for both compensatory and punitive damages. 

Under California law, punitive damages can be awarded in cases where a defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice," even if there was no contract involved. "Malice" is defined as intentional harm or, in the absence of intent, conduct that is "despicable" and shows a "willful and conscious disregard" for the safety of others. Courts have ruled that actions can be considered malicious when someone is aware of the potential dangers of their actions and deliberately chooses to ignore them.

Nearly four years ago, I took an Islam course at CBC where a key discussion revolved around whether Islam is inherently hostile. This question feels more urgent now than ever.  Since 9/11, I've witnessed a shift in media portrayal of Islam, moving from hostility and demonization of extremists to an excessive level of acceptance in America.  In 2001, it's hard to imagine a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with his family's Muslim background, being considered viable.

The Prophet Muhammad's biography raises questions for me.  My understanding of history painted a picture of Muhammad as a forceful figure who conquered tribes and imposed Islam upon them.  However, the biography portrays him as more of a martyr, misunderstood and even humbling himself while people gradually recognized the truth in his teachings. This discrepancy troubles me.

I also find similarities between Muhammad's ministry and the "miracles" attributed to him, particularly the story of multiplying food for forty men. This style of storytelling makes me believe the authors aimed to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove anything, simply living in truth and performing miracles.  This approach, I feel, diminishes the unique miracle and life of Jesus Christ and borders on appropriation.

The biography also includes numerous accounts of people converting to Islam, often relayed through third-party sources.  While intended as proof of the truth, this reliance on hearsay weakens the stories and raises doubts.

My biggest concern is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle figure.  However, historical evidence contradicts this portrayal, and I wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

Christian thought has significantly diverged from Jesus' original teachings since his death.  While traditional beliefs persist, a growing awareness and progressive trend suggest a future where Christians increasingly seek to understand and return to Jesus' core message. This movement, driven by a desire to distinguish original doctrines from later additions, will likely unfold over decades or centuries. It will involve a gradual stripping away of accumulated theological layers, ultimately leading to a revival of early Christianity, characterized by a more unified belief system and practices closely aligned with Jesus' teachings.  

This trend echoes historical patterns of reversal, such as the Roman Empire's transformation from persecutor of Christians to its official religion.  A key element of this future shift will be interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally, shedding light on the evolution of Christianity since its inception.  

Looking back, we find that Judaism, with its monotheistic beliefs and reverence for the Hebrew scriptures, served as the foundation for Christianity. Even before Roman rule in 63 B.C.E., Judaism was diverse, encompassing various groups like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and ordinary people.

Upton Sinclair's novel "The Jungle" depicts the inherent greed and self-interest of humanity, arguing that people prioritize their own well-being above all else. This is exemplified by the factory owners and managers, who relentlessly pursue profit maximization, disregarding the well-being of their workers and the environment.  Sinclair vividly portrays the detrimental impact of their actions through descriptions like "the line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," highlighting the unchecked pollution and disregard for human and animal life.  

The owners exploit their employees, forcing them to work grueling hours and subjecting them to unsafe conditions. Driven by a relentless pursuit of financial gain, they readily lay off workers without warning or support.  The absence of labor protections during this era allowed the owners to operate with impunity, perpetuating a system where workers were treated as expendable commodities.  

Sinclair argues that the workers, trapped in a cycle of poverty and despair, were essentially slaves to the system, with no avenues for escape. Even the unions, intended to protect workers, often exploited them, further deepening their plight.  He concludes that the harsh conditions in Packingtown breed immorality, comparing the situation to chattel slavery, where individuals are stripped of their dignity and agency.

Authors employ various techniques to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in readers towards significant subjects. F. Scott Fitzgerald masterfully utilizes these techniques in his novel, *The Great Gatsby*. He often juxtaposes unexpected adjective-noun pairings to create a particular aura around subjects. Fitzgerald also imbues symbols with meaning, using them to evoke desired emotional responses.  One such technique involves the use of colors, like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In *The Great Gatsby*, Fitzgerald assigns deeper meanings to white/gray, representing uniformity, with white symbolizing elegance and gray signifying age and fading grandeur. 

This meaning is established early in the novel through the frequent use of these colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently depicted in white, and white is prevalent in the attire of other characters as well. The only exception occurs during Nick's observations of Gatsby's party, where the scene is described as adorned with vibrant primary colors. Fitzgerald further reinforces the symbolic significance of white/gray by associating them with commonplace objects and settings. Nick travels through "white chasms" on his commute, names at Gatsby's parties appear as "gray names" on his timetable, and Catherine's apartment building is likened to "a long white cake of apartment-houses," emphasizing uniformity.  

White and gray are also used to describe ordinary people and places, such as Jordan and Daisy's shared "white girlhood," the "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes, and a "gray" Italian child by the railroad.

Having established the meaning of white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to convey unimportance or uniformity in relation to specific subjects. This is exemplified in his portrayal of Daisy. After a period where these colors are less prominent, Fitzgerald describes Daisy "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster." This imagery diminishes Daisy's characterization, portraying her as a more uniform and desired object rather than a complex individual.  Fitzgerald further reinforces this perception through descriptions like Daisy's "gray haze of fur collar" and her attire of "white" before Tom and Gatsby's confrontation.

San Diego County's favorable climate makes it ideal for agriculture, with diverse crops like tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, and tree fruits thriving there.  The region has a strong demand for organic produce, with local organizations often facing waiting lists for their products. Popular organic options include eggs and milk. Many organic farms also offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching, generating additional income streams. This model demonstrates how landowners can benefit from government programs while simultaneously enhancing habitat, promoting recreation, and offering educational opportunities.

Organic farming, while potentially lucrative, presents unique challenges.  It demands more labor-intensive practices for pest and weed control, fertilization, and often results in higher losses compared to conventional methods.  Smaller organic farms also lack the economies of scale enjoyed by larger operations.  Additional practices beneficial to wildlife, such as cover cropping, rotational grazing, invasive species removal, and habitat management, also contribute to increased labor costs.  These factors highlight the need for financial assistance and expertise to maximize profitability and habitat quality for landowners.

The chosen location for this scenario is a 160-acre parcel near Potrero, California, encompassing chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. Situated in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, this land is part of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which aims to protect over 100 plant and animal species, many of which are endangered or declining.  Historically, the land was inhabited by Native Americans before being used for grazing and wood production by ranchers in the late 1800s.

For this model, a real estate website was used to select a property, and available government programs were researched to assess their potential benefits for a small farmer seeking to mitigate costs and promote wildlife-friendly practices. As a model, an existing organic farm in the same area was identified to demonstrate achievable outcomes.

Culture significantly influences negotiations, shaping behaviors and expectations. It's not a single, uniform entity but rather a complex web of values, traditions, and norms that vary greatly even within a country. Overgeneralizations about entire cultures ("all Russians are stubborn") are unhelpful and inaccurate.  

Instead, negotiators should focus on understanding the specific cultural context of a negotiation and how it might affect their counterparts' perspectives and approaches.  

Cultural differences can be observed in various aspects like communication styles, decision-making processes, and workplace etiquette.  Recognizing and respecting these differences, especially when negotiating in unfamiliar territory, is crucial for building trust and achieving successful outcomes.

Moreover, corporate cultures within a nation can also differ significantly, influencing employee behavior and negotiation strategies.  Understanding these internal dynamics adds another layer of complexity to the negotiation process. 

Values are particularly important because they provide the underlying reasons behind cultural norms.  For example, a culture that prioritizes harmony might discourage confrontational negotiation tactics, while a culture that values competitiveness might lead to a more aggressive bargaining style. 

While cultural generalizations offer a starting point, it's essential for negotiators to gather information about their counterparts on a personal level to build rapport and tailor their approach effectively.

The text begins by stating that both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas believed in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To compare their arguments effectively, the author assumes this shared belief.  The author then argues that while both philosophers present valid points, neither offers a complete and convincing argument for God's existence.

Anselm's argument relies on faith and introspection. He suggests that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot truly conceive of his nonexistence. This means the proof of God lies within our own minds, accessible through faith rather than external evidence.

Aquinas, in contrast, proposes a purely rational approach. He believes God's existence can be proven through logic and empirical evidence, eliminating the need for faith. He presents five arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony, all pointing to the logical necessity of God's existence. He compares this to knowing the existence of a missing puzzle piece even without seeing it, based on the logic of the completed puzzle.

Around the 5th or 6th century BCE, a prince who later became known as Buddha was born. He renounced worldly life, achieved enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism, with Theravada being its most traditional branch. This religion, approximately 2,500 years old, has evolved significantly since Buddha's time. This evolution is evident in various aspects, such as the annual water-cutting ceremony in Sri Lanka, a Theravada Buddhist nation, where both monks and lay people participate in a ritual with religious significance despite Buddha not mentioning any such celebration. These changes encompass both superficial traditions and fundamental theological principles.  The Theravada Buddhist community, both monastic and lay, has adapted its doctrines over time due to both internal and external influences, both positive and negative.

This discussion will frequently use specific terms: "Internal" refers to forces originating from within the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic status, while "external" refers to forces from non-Buddhists. "Hostile" forces aim to harm or damage the Buddhist community, stemming from negative perceptions of Buddhism, while "benign" forces neither intend to help nor harm the community, though their actions might have unintended consequences.

Understanding the core doctrines of Theravada Buddhism is crucial. Buddhists seek refuge in the Triple Gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma (Buddhist teachings), and the Sangha (the community of monks and nuns). The Dhamma encompasses the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist scriptures: The Sutta Pitaka containing discourses, the Vinaya Pitaka outlining monastic rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka exploring Buddhist metaphysics.  Metaphysical concepts like Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence) are central to understanding the cycle of death and rebirth (Sansara).  

Overcoming Sansara requires recognizing these concepts, leading to the cessation of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) and ultimately enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for conduct, including five precepts for lay Buddhists (non-killing, non-lying, non-stealing, non-sexual misconduct, and non-use of intoxicants). Monks adhere to a more extensive set of rules.

The Four Noble Truths form the foundation of Buddhist doctrine. These truths are: 1) Dukkha (life is suffering), 2) attachment causes suffering, 3) suffering can be overcome, and 4) the path to overcome suffering is the Eightfold Path.

The United States and Mexico experienced a long-standing rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). This rivalry reached its peak during the Mexican-American War (1846-1848), where the U.S. emerged victorious, gaining Texas and the American Southwest. Numerous other conflicts punctuated this period, finally subsiding before the outbreak of World War I.  

This rivalry, rooted in clashes over religion, culture, tradition, and economic interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31), mirrors similar tensions between neighboring nations. As David M. Pletcher (1977) observed, the U.S. faced persistent diplomatic challenges with Mexico and Cuba, geographically close nations that have historically been rivals (p. 41), unlike other Latin American countries which have enjoyed generally good relations with the U.S.

Religious differences, a recurring theme in international history, played a significant role in straining the relationship. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that while 20th-century Americans opposed fascism and communism, 18th and 19th-century Americans opposed Catholicism and monarchy (p.86).  This religious divide, akin to the Cold War rivalry between the U.S. and the Soviet Union, involved both ideological clashes and competition over vital interests. However, in this case, the ideological struggle stemmed from religious preferences rather than political systems. This distrust stemmed from existing animosity between the English and Spanish, inherited by their respective colonies and posing a significant hurdle to fostering amicable relations between the two nations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) documented 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during this 57-year rivalry, primarily concerning border issues like raids from Mexican territory into the U.S. and other frontier problems (Diehl and Goerts 2000). Banditry and outlaw activity across the American border posed a major challenge until both countries deployed military force along their frontiers (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) suggests that the rivalry began to fade as Mexico increasingly relied on the U.S. economically (p. 109) and ultimately ended when American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic influence in Mexico (p.110) in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I unexpectedly became disabled due to an illness I was unaware of. At the time, I was a nurse, a profession I chose for the security it offered, a feeling I lacked in my childhood. Despite dreaming of being a scientist or journalist, I followed the advice I received: "Nursing is always in demand." Now, at 46 and single, I'm disabled and reliant on Social Security Disability. My savings are depleted, and my life is a daily struggle for security and self-esteem.

What keeps me going is the support of my family and a few close friends. Without them, I wouldn't have survived these past 15 years. This experience has taught me that life is unpredictable, and even the most prepared individuals need help during crises.

While I agree that Americans shouldn't solely rely on big government, I believe our focus should be on rebuilding trust and community support.  Instead of isolating ourselves, we should learn to help and ask for help from each other.

Conservatives often cite "rugged individualism" as the foundation of America, but our forefathers succeeded due to compassion, respect, and shared resources. Pioneers didn't conquer the West alone; they relied on each other.

So, yes, be prepared with emergency kits, supplies, and even a small farm if possible. But equally important, get to know your neighbors and build a strong community support system.

This study investigates the mechanisms driving evolutionary change in mollusk shells, particularly focusing on the genus *Prunum*.  While fully mathematically describing even simple organisms remains a challenge, mathematical modeling is increasingly used to study evolutionary processes.  

The authors utilize X-radiographic images of *Prunum* shells to define quantitative parameters that can be used in the software program CerioShell to model both real and hypothetical shell morphologies.  This allows them to explore the boundaries of possible morphological change within the genus. These models are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to gain a deeper understanding of macroevolutionary events in *Prunum*.

The study draws on the understanding of shell structure, which can be viewed as a 360-degree tube with whorls that spiral around a central columella.  Variations in whorl size and suture patterns contribute to shell diversity. The authors propose a method for counting whorls by dividing the shell in an apical view along the first suture, then counting the whorls from that line. 

Furthermore, the study highlights the potential of viewing a shell as a series of apertures traveling through time and space as the animal builds its shell.  By tracking the center of each whorl's aperture and its radius, a mathematical trajectory can be created, allowing for the modification of skeletogenesis parameters.

Despite progress in areas like water and sanitation, Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have stagnated over the last decade. While the country aims to achieve the Millennium Development Goals, improvements in maternal and child health fall short of the required pace to meet the 2015 targets. This underscores the need to bolster the overall healthcare system rather than solely relying on targeted programs.

While the percentage of births attended by skilled health workers has risen to 72%, this figure includes traditional practitioners who lack the capacity to handle complications, contributing to a high maternal mortality rate from hemorrhage.  Furthermore, the number of children under five treated for diarrhea by healthcare professionals has decreased. Postnatal care data is incomplete but reveals a concerningly low utilization rate nationwide.

Cesarean section rates remain low at 4%, with a significant disparity between urban (7%) and rural (2%) areas, highlighting the uneven distribution of healthcare access.  This inequity is further emphasized by a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting financial barriers hinder the poor's access to healthcare.

Improving neonatal and maternal care necessitates addressing this service gap. While targeted programs offer focused solutions and quicker results, they can divert funding from other crucial areas and lead to resource allocation imbalances within the health sector.  Additionally, multiple parallel programs can result in duplicated services and administrative complexities. Strengthening the overall healthcare system, therefore, emerges as a more sustainable and equitable approach.

Victorian novels are typically known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy. However, two novels from this era, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," deviate from this common theme. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and the strange and unusual,  which are not typical of Victorian literature. This unconventional approach enhances the characters by providing deeper insights into their motivations and emotions.

The following excerpt from "Oliver Twist" illustrates this:

“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)

These novels often employ mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the purpose and content vary. In "Oliver Twist," these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver's inner turmoil, his pain, and his understanding of the reality around him. When Oliver relives the shooting in chapter 28, he experiences it vividly, as if in a dream, while he desperately seeks help. This passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events that unfold and the dire state of his health, as evidenced by his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, numbing his senses so that he doesn't notice the "unseen hand" carrying him away. He relives his despair, detached from the initial shock of pain, now experiencing constant pain linked with fear rather than surprise. 

Oliver's helplessness raises the question of who is responsible for his misfortune, as it is clearly not his own doing. The shooting reinforces the idea that Oliver has little control over his life, unable to even attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at stake. This selection also suggests a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if Fagin has broken him, forcing him to accept this despair and hindering his ability to react. Otherwise, it's reasonable to assume that Oliver would have made some effort, even for the sake of his own survival.

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours."

A couple of years ago, I volunteered in an after-school program, tutoring elementary students. While I was proficient in English and reading, I was assigned to help Adrian, a third or fourth-grader who struggled with reading. His pronunciation was inconsistent, making it clear there was a deeper issue. Despite speaking fluent English, Adrian's reading difficulties stemmed from a lack of familiarity with the English alphabet. This realization came when his mother, who only spoke Spanish, visited the program. With my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate, and the truth became clear: Adrian needed help understanding the English alphabet. While I don't know if my tutoring significantly improved his reading, I hope he's doing better now.

This experience highlights the language barrier problem in schools, particularly in California. It emphasizes that reading difficulties can be hidden even for children who speak English fluently.  The key lies in addressing this challenge, not just through tutoring in English reading, but through a multi-faceted approach.

Dual language programs are a valuable asset. They benefit all children, not just those with Spanish as their first language. Research shows that students in these programs excel academically.  Concerns about resource allocation and lack of benefit for non-Spanish speaking students are unfounded. Implementing dual language programs as the norm, rather than the exception, would benefit everyone.  

While requiring all teachers to be bilingual is unrealistic, we can provide bilingual aides or tutors to support students.

From a young age, many of us are taught about a power greater than ourselves, something beyond our understanding.  Some seek answers in organized religion, while others find solace in introspection.  We often inherit the beliefs of our parents, but some reject them entirely, clinging to the idea that our own limited experiences define all that exists. Our values may shift over time as we search for meaning and purpose. Ultimately, each individual embarks on a unique journey to define their spirituality, seeking guidance and enlightenment.

One evening, while sitting on the porch with my father, rain drumming against the roof, he told me his favorite bird was a cardinal. He seemed lost in thought, his gaze fixed on the downpour.  He had grown frail, his clothes hanging loosely on his weakened frame, his hair thinning. He avoided my eyes, leaving me feeling isolated and afraid to voice the fear that gnawed at me – the fear of losing him. I held him close, drawn to his presence in the dimming twilight.

My father died in December of that year, just five days after my 22nd birthday. The treatments had only prolonged his suffering, offering no real relief.  I questioned the existence of a benevolent God who would allow such pain.  Alone in the darkness, I found no solace in prayer. 

I had chosen not to witness his final moments, unable to bear the sight of life fading. I wanted to remember him as he was, not as he was dying. I knew him better than anyone else, and I believed he wouldn't want me to be a mere observer at the end of his journey. For three days, I retreated into myself, waiting for the news, but no one called.

The Gothic novel, as Ian Watt argues, is a paradoxical blend of "Old" and "New." It has been both criticized and celebrated, sometimes for its perceived lack of depth and sometimes for its ability to evoke a sense of awe and terror (Burke). Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," considered the first Gothic novel, fused elements of both ancient and modern romances to create a new literary form. Walpole combined traditional theatrical elements with a more modern, nature-inspired style to craft what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4).  The Gothic genre frequently draws upon medieval Gothic architecture, theatre, and traditions. Despite this, the term "Gothic" was often used pejoratively at the time, associated with outdatedness and a lack of sophistication compared to the perceived advancements of the contemporary era.  The unique combination of theatrical elements and the novel's introspective nature, allowing readers a glimpse into the characters' minds, has ensured the enduring appeal of Gothic literature, making it both timeless and refreshingly new to readers separated from its origins.

One prominent theme in Gothic novels is chivalry. The medieval ideal of chivalry, the training of a noble knight, is both preserved and transformed in "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry holds particular significance for Gothic writers because it represents a bygone era of bravery, honor, and competence – qualities that many, especially Walpole, believed were lacking in modern society. By employing chivalric concepts and manners, the "Gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized, foreshadowing the genre's evolution towards Romanticism. This romanticization serves as an attempt to elevate the present by drawing inspiration from a perceived golden age. 

Walpole, writing during a period of political turmoil and personal adversity, may have been lamenting the perceived decline of morality and inherent goodness in society. This sentiment is reflected in characters like Frederic, whose description emphasizes traditional chivalric traits:

[The description of Frederic includes a great many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is, foremost, a prince, he has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy that he leaves, and is currently supposed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course exaggerated, bringing the soon to be Gothic trope of excess into play (66).]

Supply chain management encompasses the entire journey of goods, from a customer's order to the delivery of the final product.  Coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, it involves strategically planning, executing, and controlling all aspects of the supply chain to effectively meet customer needs quickly and efficiently.  

The six core elements of supply chain management are production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. By managing these elements, businesses aim to deliver exceptional customer service.

Production, the first stage, lays the groundwork for the entire process. It involves determining when, where, and how products will be made, based on market analysis and customer demand. Understanding customer needs is crucial, and managers rely on market trends to make informed decisions about product types and quantities. 

Once production plans are established, managers select the optimal location for manufacturing, considering factors like production volume, quality, and customer satisfaction.  

Next, the focus shifts to scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment to ensure smooth and efficient production.  Meticulous planning at this stage is essential to avoid costly delays and inefficiencies in the long run.  

The second key element is supply, which involves strategic decisions regarding a company's core production capabilities and outsourcing partnerships.  A company might have multiple production divisions, each with specialized equipment and expertise. Managers must strategically allocate work among these divisions or consider outsourcing to other companies to enhance efficiency, flexibility, and cost-effectiveness.  Outsourcing is often chosen to achieve "velocity," meaning the ability to deliver quality products quickly while minimizing costs.

A sign held by actress Ellen Page reads "Hitler is alive in Burma," highlighting the severity of the situation in Myanmar. This Southeast Asian nation has been under the oppressive rule of a military junta since 1962. In 2007, peaceful protests, known as the "Saffron Revolution," erupted, led by Buddhist monks. While initially tolerated, the demonstrations were met with escalating violence as the military junta cracked down, raiding monasteries and suppressing dissent. Foreign journalists were targeted, with some killed or imprisoned. The true death toll remains unknown, but reports suggest thousands may have perished during the crackdown. This incident is a stark reminder of the historical trend of governments suppressing dissent and maintaining absolute control.  

Throughout history, authoritarian regimes have employed violence to silence opposition. From ancient Roman emperors claiming divine authority to modern-day examples like the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989, where hundreds, possibly thousands, were killed, and the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s, the suppression of dissent has been a recurring theme. These atrocities serve as a chilling reminder of the dangers of unchecked power and the importance of protecting human rights.

Duke Ellington's enduring legacy in jazz stems from his longevity and his remarkable ability to shape his orchestra over the years. While his piano playing is often subtle in his compositions, Ellington excelled at crafting intricate and rich pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his musicians. He provided a framework for improvisation while simultaneously writing tightly orchestrated sections and phrases that showcased the unique styles of his band members. Through this approach, he also established a distinctive orchestral tone, creating original and cohesive sounds for each piece. Ellington's mastery over his musicians' individual sounds and their collective ensemble blend enabled him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant works in jazz history. 

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative use of voice in jazz, citing "Creole Love Call" as an example where voice is treated as an instrument. This early composition demonstrates Ellington's ability to add texture and color through voice without relying on lyrics, and also showcases his skill at complementing the styles of his soloists, a characteristic that runs throughout his career.  "Creole Love Call," a slow blues piece in twelve-bar form, consists of six choruses, each with distinct musical developments. The piece features a call-and-response pattern between voice and reeds, a muted trumpet solo, a soaring clarinet solo, and a climactic chorus with heightened intensity. 

Ellington's use of voice to enrich the sonic palette of this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait that permeates his entire body of work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his mastery of tight orchestration with his keen ear for tonal color. He achieves this by using a call-and-response between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing, blending the vocal elements of Miley's trumpet playing with the instrumental qualities of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. This concept is further explored in "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," where Ellington utilizes Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a prominent member of his orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone.

From the age of fourteen, a persistent sense of incompleteness had lingered within her. This yearning, which intensified as she reached seventeen, had evolved from a desire for something material to a longing for a companion. Despite attracting the attention of boys who attempted to court her, none truly captured her interest.  This lack of romantic inclination puzzled her, leading to years of introspection and countless theories, yet she remained unable to pinpoint the cause. She continued to navigate life, forever questioning her desires.

Her family life was typically peaceful. Her parents, known for their calm demeanor, rarely argued, and disagreements with their daughter were equally infrequent. The only point of contention arose from her assertive and independent nature, which contrasted with their more subdued personalities. Although her parents were tranquil, their daughter's vibrant and sociable nature made her a beloved member of the family.

However, this day deviated from the norm. While searching for inspiration, she heard her mother's distressed cry from the kitchen. Rushing to her aid, she found her mother lying on the floor in apparent pain, moaning in short gasps.  Concerned, her daughter immediately knelt beside her, asking what was wrong. Her mother, her voice strained, managed to whisper, "Sweetheart, I need you to take me to the hospital."

Recognizing the urgency of the situation, her daughter quickly helped her mother into the car and drove her to the hospital.  The sterile smell of disinfectant and the palpable fear in the air did little to penetrate her focus, as her sole concern was her mother's well-being. She quickly guided her mother into the hospital and called for medical assistance.  Doctors and nurses quickly gathered around, placing her mother on a gurney and rushing her away for immediate treatment.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to reach a vase from a high shelf.

This study investigated the link between following a Mediterranean diet and the risk of heart disease and stroke in women. The "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score" was used to measure adherence to this diet, which emphasizes plant-based foods, healthy fats, and fish while limiting animal products and saturated fats.

Previous research showed a connection between the Mediterranean diet and reduced risk of heart disease and overall mortality. However, this study specifically focused on stroke and stroke-related deaths. 

The study followed over 74,000 women for 20 years, tracking their diet through repeated questionnaires and medical records.  The researchers adjusted for factors like age, smoking, weight, and physical activity to ensure accurate results. 

The findings showed that women who closely followed the aMed diet had a lower risk of developing heart disease and stroke compared to those who didn't.

The 2007 financial crisis in the United States had devastating consequences, including rising unemployment, a collapsed housing market, and the downfall of major corporations. This crisis continues to have lingering effects, prompting the question of its origins and potential solutions. The crisis stemmed from irresponsible political decisions that encouraged banks and businesses to issue subprime loans to borrowers with poor creditworthiness. These loans were packaged and sold as complex financial instruments, such as mortgage-backed securities and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs), further fueling the problem.

The roots of the crisis can be traced back to the Clinton administration's actions in 1999, when relaxed lending regulations aimed at boosting the president's popularity inadvertently created conditions for the subprime crisis. These policies pressured institutions like Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac to increase lending to low- and moderate-income borrowers, ultimately leading to a surge in risky mortgages. As predicted by journalist Steven Holmes, this reckless lending would have dire consequences, ultimately resulting in a financial meltdown.

Several factors contributed to the economic collapse, including the complexity of new mortgage products like adjustable-rate mortgages and mortgage-backed securities. These instruments intertwined various sectors of the economy with the housing market, leading to widespread overleveraging. When the housing bubble burst, financial institutions holding these mortgage-backed securities suffered massive losses.  

The crisis reached a critical point in 2007, when the top five U.S. investment banks held a staggering $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt. This represented approximately 30% of the U.S. GDP. Leading institutions like Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers collapsed, while others, such as Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley, were forced to restructure and submit to stricter regulations. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, burdened with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control.

Exposition, or the act of explaining background information in a story, can be a tricky thing. While it's necessary to give readers context, too much exposition can be boring and make them lose interest.  Think of it like this: exposition is like a shoulder demon whispering in your ear, urging you to dump all the information about your characters and their pasts onto the page.  Instead, try to "show, don't tell."  

For example, instead of stating that a character's husband was a loving and important part of her life, show it through their interactions and actions.  Describe his kind words, his gestures, and how she reacts to his presence.  This will create a stronger emotional connection with the reader and make the husband's death more impactful.

Similarly, when introducing new characters, avoid simply listing their facts and figures.  Instead, weave those details into their interactions and experiences.  Let the reader discover their past through their words, actions, and relationships.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio on August 13, 2011. The first was a live broadcast by NBC 4. The lead story covered the stabbing of a woman in Ashley, Ohio, by Shad Hostettler. Though the woman's name wasn't mentioned, her husband's mugshot was shown. The report was brief, lasting about two minutes, and only stated that he had been arrested after stabbing his wife multiple times. 

The next story involved an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers who was critically injured in a shooting at Sharon Woods. There were no arrests or suspects at the time, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story felt shorter than others, leading me to believe it might be due to the victim being Black. I've noticed a pattern where minority victims of crime receive less media attention compared to white victims.

Subsequent stories covered a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, the forecast for the weekend, and a robbery at a UDF store on Clime Road. The robbery story focused on details about the suspect, including his race and physical appearance, which I found disproportionate.

Finally, the news reported on Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin from Texas sentenced to 300 months (25 years) in prison for drug distribution. I found it interesting that they emphasized the number of months rather than years. They also mentioned his Hispanic ethnicity, which seemed irrelevant to the story.

The relationship between brothers is unique, characterized by a powerful and unbreakable bond. This bond encompasses a wide range of emotions, including love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers possess a deep understanding of each other, surpassing any other relationship. They see their own reflection in their brothers, revealing their true selves. This profound connection is most evident during times of crisis, revealing the inherent goodness or evil within the bond. The emotions that arise from this fraternal link often come at a significant cost, and understanding their consequences is crucial.  

The story "The Scarlet Ibis" explores this theme of brotherly love and conflict.  Set against a lush and vivid backdrop, two brothers embark on a journey that ultimately proves futile.  The story culminates in a clash between bitter disappointment and intense pride, leaving only one brother alive. The author uses direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and his interactions with his brother to illustrate the complexities of their relationship. The narrator's point of view further enriches the story, revealing the protagonist's internal struggles and his perception of the world, which heavily influence his actions.

The protagonist's primary emotion is pride.  From their first outing together to their final, tragic journey, he harbors resentment towards Doodle. He yearns for a brother who can keep up with his adventurous spirit, someone who can share in his aspirations. Doodle's physical limitations, stemming from a weak heart, shatter these dreams.  The protagonist's frustration and anger reach a disturbing peak when he contemplates harming Doodle, revealing a dark side to his character. However, Doodle's innocent smile softens his heart, suggesting a deeper love beneath the surface.

The human brain is a complex system for processing information, and our understanding of it has evolved alongside technological advancements. Early metaphors compared it to basic tools like wax tablets and papyrus, later progressing to books and, most recently, computers. However, these analogies have limitations and can lead to misconceptions.

Information processing begins with sensory input, where physical stimuli are converted into electrochemical signals. The brain then processes this information through both bottom-up and top-down mechanisms. Bottom-up processing analyzes basic elements like color, shape, and edges to build a perception, while top-down processing utilizes existing knowledge to guide and speed up recognition. For example, when viewing a black box against a white background, bottom-up processing identifies the individual features, while top-down processing helps us quickly recognize it as a box rather than a hole.

An attention filter regulates which information is prioritized and made accessible to various cognitive processes. This filter ensures we focus on relevant details, like our name in a noisy room, while filtering out less important information, such as individual blades of grass. Attention constantly modulates processing at different stages.

For information to be processed, it must be stored in various memory types, including sensory, working, and long-term. Encoding involves converting information into a format suitable for storage, with different encoding methods for different sensory inputs. Maintaining information in working memory may rely on electrical signals looping through neurons, while long-term memory is thought to be stored in protein structures.

Various models attempt to explain how knowledge is organized in the brain, drawing on insights from memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that concepts are represented as nodes interconnected based on their relationships, creating a web of connections between ideas.

Aldous Huxley's novel *Brave New World* critiques the dangers of both technological advancement and the capitalist system that fuels it. The novel depicts a dystopian society where community is prioritized over individual expression, and citizens are conditioned from birth to seek instant gratification above all else.  They become pawns in a system controlled by the World Controller, adhering to a single, imposed ideology. 

Through a Marxist lens, Huxley reveals his distrust of these emerging systems. Terms like "homogeny" and "reification," central to Marxist thought, underscore the novel's critique of the flaws inherent in the economic system of Huxley's time.

Capitalism is satirized through the concept of "false consciousness," where the general population is unaware of their true economic position due to their focus on personal gain. This ideological control, akin to the manipulation of the proletariat, is evident in the conditioning of *Brave New World's* citizens. The lower classes (Delta, Gamma, etc.) lack independent will; their desire to consume and indulge is amplified through hypnopædia, a sleep-learning technique, by the World Controller.

Hegemony, the dominance of one social group over others, is also evident. The lower classes remain oblivious to this manipulation, unwittingly accepting the capitalist and consumerist ideology. The upper classes, while aware, choose complacency, accepting their privileged position.

Relationships in *Brave New World* are superficial and devoid of genuine connection. The characters, even major ones, lack depth, possibly suggesting that technology and capitalism stifle individual freedom and expression. Love and intense emotions are absent, replaced by superficial interactions, often characterized by objectification and transactional attitudes towards sex.

The citizens' acceptance of their societal roles further illustrates the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their unquestioning obedience mirrors Marxist ideas about the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they consume, obey, and conform.

As a student at University Park for the past two and a half years, I've experienced the campus's growing pains firsthand.  Navigating the sprawling campus can be a real challenge, especially when traveling from the East Halls dorms, which are located quite a distance from the central area. During my freshman year, it often took me up to 25 minutes to walk to classes in buildings like Willard, and that's not even accounting for inclement weather.  I learned that the area surrounding the East Halls used to be vast and undeveloped, but it's now filled with new buildings, sports facilities, and apartments, making the campus even more spread out.  

The expansion raises the question: how can we best address the mobility challenges on campus?  

The answer, I believe, lies in bicycles.  While bicycles themselves aren't a complete solution, they offer a sustainable and efficient way to travel.  People need to be encouraged to use them, and the campus infrastructure should be designed to accommodate cyclists. 

I recently spoke to a friend who rediscovered the joy of cycling after a break. He remarked that it's the most practical way to get around campus.  Bicycling is not only good for your health but also the most efficient mode of transportation. A little bit of exertion alongside a healthy breakfast can take you miles. 

Living off campus now, I've found that having a bike is a game-changer. My daily commute to Thomas building, a 25-minute walk, is reduced to a brisk 5 minutes on my bike.  However, navigating Pollock Road, the most direct route, can be challenging. While walking has its merits, my busy schedule doesn't allow for it. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to each day, amounting to over two and a half hours each week. That's simply not feasible.

original_texts:
Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.
